   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_03_16_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>Cheltenham
                  <date when="1818-03-16">16 March<lb/> 1818</date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName></persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Your good and kind heart<lb/>
               will rejoice to hear that our<lb/>
               dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> is much better.<lb/>
               I wish you could see how clear<lb/>
               his eyes look and how much<lb/>
               the flushing in his face has<lb/>
               diminished since he has taken<lb/>
               the cold shower Bath. The waters<lb/>
               have been of use to his bowels &amp;<lb/>
               <del></del> the company of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">my brother</persName><lb/>
               who has been so good as to join<lb/>
               us here has given him <choice><orig>re-<lb/>
               -newed</orig><reg>renewed</reg></choice> spirits - As <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">my brother</persName><lb/>
               must return to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> on <choice><orig>Wednes<lb/>
               -day</orig><reg>Wednesday</reg></choice> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> means to <choice><orig>accompa<lb/>
               =ny</orig><reg>accompany</reg></choice> him thither - and I am<lb/>
               sure that nothing could give<lb/>
               <note>On this page of the letter, when referring to her brother, Frances Anne Edgeworth is likely referring to her brother, Sir Francis Beaufort. Though she has two brothers, due to his assignment with the Royal Navy, it seems likely that he would be based in London at this time.</note>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_03_16_page02.jpg"/>
               him the pleasure or be of<lb/>
               more use to him than <del>a</del> letters<lb/>
               from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Doctor Brinkley</persName> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WollW1">Doctor<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">Wollaston</hi></persName> - <hi rend="underline"><persName ref="./Personography.xml#PondJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Pond</persName></hi> or any<lb/>
               other scientific man who<lb/>
               would admit a young Irishman<lb/>
               who is ardent in the pursuit of<lb/>
               knowledge among the number<lb/>
               of their acquaintance.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I expect that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> will<lb/>
               find great improvement &amp;<lb/>
               great amusement in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName><lb/>
               not in the common way of<lb/>
               young man's dissipation but<lb/>
               in the rational enlargement<lb/>
               of his sphere of knowledge<lb/>
               and the sense of acquirement<lb/>
               in his own mind.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I hope the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName> is quite <choice><orig>recover<lb/>
               -ed</orig></choice> from the cold which had<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_1818_03_16_page03.jpg"/>
               confined him to his bed at the<lb/>
               time when you were so<lb/>
               good as to call on us - and<lb/>
               as I suppose he is going <unclear>to</unclear><lb/>
               <unclear></unclear> for Easter is not<lb/>
               gone - I beg he will convey<lb/>
               to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ3">John Brinkley</persName> the good<lb/>
               intelligence of his friends<lb/>
               being better along with<lb/>
               my kind remembrances<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               To the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Doctor</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinS1">Miss B.</persName> pray<lb/>
               give my love - and believe<lb/>
               me <hi rend="underline">always dear</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> B.</persName><lb/>
               Your obliged &amp; affectionate<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">F. Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Edgeworth's</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1"><choice><orig>Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi></orig><reg>Captain</reg></choice> Beaufort's</persName> Letters</addrLine><lb/>
                  <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName></addrLine><lb/>
                  <addrLine><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dunsink-Observatory_IE">Observatory</placeName></addrLine><lb/>
                  <addrLine>Near <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName></addrLine><lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
